data.description:
Annual CSU Haunted Takeover

MANKATO, Minn. –The Student Events Team will be putting on their Annual CSU Haunted Takeover. It will be a fearful experience.

This Halloween season the Student Events Team will put fear into you with the theme of, “Scarry TV.” It will entail new routes within the Centennial Student Union with transformation of separate rooms that will be created into Scary TV Shows. This year, there is a new and scarier element to the takeover of the CSU. It’s the first outdoor element, with weather permitting. Be prepared for a night of screams

Enter if you dare the CSU doors located across from the fountain. This is free to students and open to the public for a $5 admission. Make sure to wear closed toe shoes, as well as, no outside food or drink is allowed in the haunted takeover. Dress appropriately for the weather. Arrive early to avoid long lines!

"I am excited to hopefully have the turnout of 1500+ students show up to take part in the festivities. It’s really fun and haunting event that each year gets better and better." –Dustin Slaughter, Student Events Team Special Events.

No cameras or flash photography are prohibited. Age viewers’ discretion is advised.

The Student Events Team is a student-led organization that produces fun, interactive, educational events where students make lifelong memories and celebrate their Maverick pride.

All participants video a custom made scary movie and movie with rules before entering.

High touch point for the people in line. They have to talk to you.

onsite.student_data_policy:
In support of our mission, the University of Maryland Division of Student Affairs accepts sponsorships under strict guidelines. The Division of Student Affairs reserves the right to refuse any sponsorship we believe is incompatible with our mission and values. 

Sponsorship Guidelines
		
•	The Division of Student Affairs has sole discretion for determining the types of sponsorships that will be accepted.  The presence of a sponsorship does not imply in any manner endorsement of the sponsor or sponsor’s product. 
 
•	The Division of Student Affairs will not accept a sponsorship that, in our sole opinion, is not in good taste. We will not permit a) a sponsorship involving illegal or objectionable products or services, or b) a sponsorship that is offensive to any individual or group of individuals based on age, color, national origin, race, religion, sex, sexual orientation, or handicap.

•	The sponsorship will not be accepted if it promotes any of the following: alcohol, firearms, ammunition, fireworks, gambling, pornography, tobacco or feminine hygiene products.

•	Sponsored content on our sites, in publications and other collateral materials is clearly labeled as such and the sponsoring organizations are identified.

•	The Division of Student Affairs reserves the right to reject, cancel, or remove any sponsorship at any time. We will provide reasonable notice to the sponsor upon rejection, cancellation, or removal of any sponsorship.

•	No sponsorship shall be permitted that may injure the good name or reputation of the University of Maryland or the Division of Student Affairs.

Sponsor Tabling Guidelines
•	The Division of Student Affairs, Adele H. Stamp Student Union-Center for Campus Life, and Campus Recreation Services has designated space for sponsor tabling. Dates must be approved and scheduled in advance by the appropriate Division of Student Affairs sponsorship liaison. Cancellations can only be honored if they are made 7 days in advance to the appropriate Division of Student Affairs sponsorship liaison. Dates are based on availability and on a first come first serve basis.  Exclusivity is not guaranteed. 

•	During tabling days or events, sponsors may not solicit students, faculty/staff, parents, etc. to sign any binding contracts, account agreements or commitment for a good/service. Sponsors may however allow people to give contact information to use at a later date. The sponsor cannot require this information to be provided in exchange for an item, certificate, entry into a raffle, etc. 

•	Sponsors may not distribute food items during their tabling days. Sponsors may however work with the Division of Student Affairs Department of Dining Services to arrange an on-campus food vendor from the Stamp Food Court to purchase and distribute food from an on-campus food vendor. Packaged food may be considered if it is a Pepsi product or a Pepsi subsidiary product that is pre-packaged and sealed, but must receive prior approval from the Division of Student Affairs Department of Dining Services.  Sampling and/or open food is not allowed at all.

data.description:
Trap&B Artist Fetty Wap to Perform at Minnesota State Mankato
Tickets Available for Public Purchase
Mankato, Minn. – Trap&B artist Fetty Wap will perform on the Summit and Jacob Heights stage in Minnesota State University, Mankato’s Myers Field House during the University’s Homecoming week. American rapper Silentó will open for Fetty Wap 


Fetty Wap is an American rapper, singer and songwriter whose debut single "Trap Queen" reached number two on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100 chart in May 2015. Other Fetty Wap top 10 hits include “My Way” and “679.”


Among his many awards and nominations, Fetty Wap, won the category of Top New Artist at the 2016 Billboard Music Awards and was named Best New Artist at the 2016 iHeartRadio Music Awards.


Silentó’s debut single, “Watch Me (Whip/Nae Nae),” reached number three on the Hot 100 list, and the song’s YouTube video has reached over 1.5 billion views. Silentó was nominated for Top New Artist at the 2016 Billboard Music Awards.


The concert, presented by Minnesota State Mankato’s Student Events Team and radio station Hot 96.7, is for all ages.


Tickets may be purchased online at www.mnsuevents.com or at Minnesota State Mankato’s Student Activities front desk, located in the Centennial Student Union, Room 173.


Public tickets are $30. A limited number of tickets will be made available to Minnesota State Mankato students for an “early-bird special” price of $5. After those tickets are distributed, Minnesota State Mankato students may purchase tickets for $15 each. Student guest tickets (one per student) are available for $25.


Last year all student tickets sold out in six hours, said Bill Tourville, assistant director of campus programs at Minnesota State Mankato.


Homecoming VIP pre-party tickets are $50 for students and the public. The party package, sponsored by Summit and Jacob Heights and hosted by Hot 96.7, includes free food, beverages, signed merchandise, early access to the best general admission spot and a picture with Silentó.


Doors will open at 6:30 p.m. on concert night, and there is no re-entry to the concert once a patron leaves. Parking will be available in Lot 20. No outside food, beverages, backpacks or flash photography is allowed. Minnesota State Mankato bans weapons on campus and is an alcohol-, drug- and tobacco-free campus. Use of substances will result in removal from the concert.


A special reception with free tickets to the concert is available to alumni of the Student Events Team, IMPACT and University Programs. For more information on the special reception or concert, contact Bill Tourville by email at william.tourville@mnsu.edu or by phone at 507-389-6076.


Minnesota State Mankato’s Student Events team is a student-led organization that produces fun, interactive and educational events for students to create lifelong memories and celebrate their Maverick pride. The Student Events Team meets every Tuesday at 4 p.m. in Centennial Student Union 245, and students interested in joining or volunteering with the group are welcome to attend the meetings.


Minnesota State Mankato, a comprehensive university with 14,712 students, is part of the Minnesota State system, which includes 30 colleges and seven universities.

data.description: The Associated Student Government and Activities Programming Board are working together to host our first annual Bronco Day - a day to celebrate being apart of the Santa Clara University community! We want to have food, booths for particular grade levels that will have certain giveaways and activities, amusement park rides, music and much, much more! We are hoping to have different organizations from around campus (Athletics, the Multicultural Center, the Alumni Office, the Center for Sustainability, etc.) host different activities as well. Bronco Day will end with our Spring Concert; while we are still finalizing the artist for our Spring Concert, in the past we have had Walk the Moon, Sage the Gemini, Chance the Rapper, Misterwives and Young the Giant.

onsite.student_data_policy:
"Students must have the choice to share (or not share) their contact information.
 The data collected must be used for that company's purposes only and cannot be shared or sold to others without the consent of the students.
 If students are being put on a mailing or email list, then students need to have the option to unsubscribe at any time they want upon request.
 No personal information may be collected, i.e. no social security numbers, student ID#s, financial information; instead only names, email addresses, and phone numbers may be collected."

data.description: During the day, we have a free-to-attend music festival on Walnut park featuring mid-level music acts in addition to brand activations and activities like inflatables, carnival games, etc. Mayfest is the best opportunity for on-site brand tents/immersive experiences. The event normally attracts 10k students and is closed to the public. At night, Block Party occurs in the Carrier Dome and is a ticketed concert featuring top-tier acts (The Chainsmokers/Chance The Rapper were last year) that attracts 12-13k people. This concert is open to the public and we do not offer on-site activations. That being said, we would love to discuss on-stage banner sponsorships as an opportunity to have a physical presence in front of 12,000 captive college-aged students.
